rampton, Norfolk, England":"Brampton, Norfolk, England","Banham, Norfolk, England":"Banham, Norfolk, England","Barrington, South Somerset, Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Barrington, Somerset, England","Old Romney, Kent, England":"Old Romney, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Farnham, Surrey, England":"Farnham, Surrey, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Harley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from either of two places called Harley (Shropshire, Yorkshire). The Shropshire placename derives from Old English <i>hær</i> ‘rock, heap of stones’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’. The Yorkshire placename derives from Old English <i>hara</i> ‘hare’ or <i>hær</i> + <i>hlāw</i> ‘mound, hill’, later replaced by <i>lēah</i>.","Irish (Donegal): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hEarghaile</b> ‘descendant of <i>Earghal</i>’, a variant of the personal name <i>Fearghal</i> without the initial <i>F-</i>. This name has also become   Herley   and   Hurley  . Compare   Arrell   and   Harrell  .","Scottish (Fife): habitational name from any of several places called Harlaw in Midlothian, Peeblesshire, and Berwickshire, named in Older Scots with <i>hare</i> ‘gray’ + <i>law</i> ‘hill’."],"variants":[{"name":"Herley","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Art, Cormac.","Irish: variant of   Hurley  , probably via   Herlihy  .","English: variant of   Harley   or   Hurley  ."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Alice de Harley was born in 1463, in Brampton, Norfolk, England. She married John Bishop in 1479, in Old Romney, Kent, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died in 1527, in Itteringham, Norfolk, England, at the age of 64."},"et":{"1463–1527":"1463–1527","1460–1507":"1460–1507","1460–Male":"1460–Surnud","1483–1503":"1483–1503","1486–1504":"1486–1504","1486–1569":"1486–1569","1569":"1569","1503":"1503","1479":"1479","about 1503":"umbes 1503","1486":"1486","1463":"1463","1483":"1483","1460":"1460","1507":"1507","1527":"1527","1504":"1504","Pillerton Priors, Warwickshire, England":"Pillerton Priors, Warwickshire, England","Itteringham, Norfolk, England":"Itteringham, Norfolk, England","Brampton, Norfolk, England":"Brampton, Norfolk, England","Banham, Norfolk, England":"Banham, Norfolk, England","Barrington, South Somerset, Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Barrington, Somerset, E